'''Batrachology''' is the branch of [[zoology]] concerned with the study of [[amphibian]]s including [[frog]]s and [[toad]]s, [[salamander]]s, [[newt]]s, and [[caecilian]]s. It is a sub-discipline of [[herpetology]], which includes also non-avian [[Reptile|reptiles]] ([[snake]]s, [[lizard]]s, [[amphisbaenia|amphisbaenids]], [[turtle]]s, [[terrapin]]s, [[tortoise]]s, [[crocodilia|crocodilians]], and the [[tuatara]]). '''Batrachologists''' may study the [[evolution]], [[ecology]], [[ethology]], or [[anatomy]] of amphibians.
Amphibians are [[Ectotherm|cold blooded]] vertebrates largely found in damp habitats although many species have special behavioural adaptations that allow them to live in deserts, trees, underground and in regions with wide seasonal variations in temperature. There are over 7250 [[species]] of amphibians.<ref name="AmphibiaWeb">{{cite web|url=http://amphibiaweb.org/ |title=AmphibiaWeb |publisher=AmphibiaWeb |accessdate=2014-03-27}}</ref>
==Notable batrachologists of history== * [[Jean Marius René Guibé]] * [[Gabriel Bibron]] * [[Oskar Boettger]] * [[George Albert Boulenger]] * [[Edward Drinker Cope]] * [[François Marie Daudin]] * [[Franz Werner]]
